Forms (Part 1): <form>, <input>, type="text"

What is a Form?
--A form is used to collect user input. You’ll learn to create a basic form with text input.

Example Code:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Day 15: HTML Forms - Part 1</title>
</head>
<body>

  <h1>Day 15: Basic Form</h1>

  <form action="/submit" method="post">
    <label for="fullname">Full Name:</label><br>
    <input type="text" id="fullname" name="fullname" placeholder="Enter your name"><br><br>

    <label for="email">Email:</label><br>
    <input type="text" id="email" name="email" placeholder="Enter your email"><br><br>

    <input type="submit" value="Submit">
  </form>

</body>
</html>

✅ Explanation:
--<form> wraps the entire form.
--action="/submit" is where the form data goes (can be a real or dummy URL).
--<input type="text"> creates text boxes.
--name="..." lets the backend know what each input field is for.
--placeholder="..." gives users a hint on what to enter.
